leader","primary_url":"https://www.marybakereddylibrary.org/research/from-the-papers-discovering-one-of-the-brightest-women-in-oakland/","primary_url_label":"Mary Baker Eddy Library"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Her 1887 dam patent informed Hoover Dam","body":"In 1887 she patented a dam and reservoir system using a series of ascending dams, each braced by the water against the one below. Congress adopted that mechanism when it approved the Hoover Dam project in 1928."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Walnut Queen of Whittier within five years","body":"Widowed at 39 with four daughters and a near-bankrupt ranch, she taught herself scientific agriculture by reading journals. Within five years she planted 150 acres of walnuts and became the largest commercial walnut grower in the United States."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"I had the courage of ignorance and determination","body":"Her husband Charles Lyman Strong had committed suicide after business failures, leaving her with four daughters and an unprofitable ranch near Whittier. Of her self-taught success she later said: 'I had the courage of ignorance and plenty of determination to back it up.'"},{"number":4,"category":"social_reform","header":"Traveled with Susan B. Anthony for women's suffrage","body":"She traveled with Susan B. Anthony promoting women's suffrage, hosting Anthony at her Rancho del Fuerte in 1895. She was the first woman member of the Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce and the first woman delegate to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce convention in 1918."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"It was thought of by a woman","body":"Appearing before Congress in 1918 to urge a series of Colorado River dams, she said: 'It was thought of by a woman.' Congress eventually built the Hoover Dam (1935) and the All-American Canal (1942) — both reflecting her ideas."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01123","date_ye